{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621934"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:59:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:59:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16779"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16779"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70537"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9470"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56001"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5529"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23678"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70537"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPopulation dynamics are fundamental to understanding demographic changes in communities. Various factors contribute to changes in population size over time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how to calculate the total population growth rate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Birth rate minus death rate only","Immigration rate minus emigration rate only","Birth rate plus immigration rate only","(Birth rate minus death rate) plus (immigration rate minus emigration rate)","Death rate plus emigration rate only"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe total population growth rate is calculated as \u003Cstrong\u003E(birth rate minus death rate) plus (immigration rate minus emigration rate)\u003C/strong\u003E. This formula accounts for both natural increase (births minus deaths) and net migration (immigration minus emigration).\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBirth rate minus death rate only\u003C/strong\u003E calculates natural increase but fails to account for population changes due to migration.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmigration rate minus emigration rate only\u003C/strong\u003E considers net migration but omits the natural population changes from births and deaths.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBirth rate plus immigration rate only\u003C/strong\u003E includes only population-increasing factors while neglecting the decreasing factors of deaths and emigration.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeath rate plus emigration rate only\u003C/strong\u003E considers only population-decreasing factors while neglecting the increasing factors of births and immigration.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding population dynamics is crucial for public health planning, resource allocation, and predicting future healthcare needs of communities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Population growth rate is calculated as (birth rate - death rate) + (immigration rate - emigration rate).","Natural increase refers only to the difference between birth rate and death rate, excluding migration.","Migration affects population size through immigration (increases) and emigration (decreases)."],"references":["Canudas-Romo V, Shen T, Payne CF. The Components of Change in Population Growth Rates. Demography. 